post_text: Loads of smiles behind the masks as more than 2,800 kids returned to our elementary classrooms today under a hybrid model combining modified in-person instruction with distance learning. The remainder of the District’s elementary school students continue to be enrolled in 100% distance learning through the LosAl@Home program. With Orange County moving today to the less restrictive Red tier of state COVID-19 monitoring, our middle schools and Los Al High are scheduled to re-open under the hybrid model later this month. Welcome back!

post_text: Today was the last day of our Grab and Go meal service program at Los Alamitos Elementary and McGaugh Elementary schools. But fear not! Bon appetit!

post_text: Smiles — and joyful tears — abounded as 534 carloads of Los Al High seniors and their families took a two-hour graduation victory lap through Rossmoor, cheered on by many hundreds more friends, former elementary and middle school teachers, counselors, District Board members and staff, and neighbors who stood, socially distanced, at the curb. Local police officers and firefighters, sheriff's deputies and the Highway Patrol escorted them safely along the route. Congratulations Class of 2020. It's been a year to remember! #LosAlBetterTogether

post_text:
Here's a quick and easy "stay-at-home" activity: Complete the Census. Go to https://2020census.gov/ and click RESPOND. You almost certainly got one of these little blue post cards in the mail with your Census ID emblazoned above your address. Enter that code and you're off! Can't find that little card or any other mailings from the Census, no problem: Click the "I can't find my Census ID" button and they'll find it for you!

Completing the Census is crucially important to ensure public services and funding for our schools, hospitals, and fire departments, as well as determining your representation in Congress. Making sure everyone completes the Census is even more important during the disruption of the coronavirus pandemic. So feel free to share this info with neighbors, friends and family!

post_text: Following the guidance of Governor Gavin Newsom and state education officials, we sadly share with you that all our campuses will be closed to students for the remainder of the 2019-20 school year. All District facilities, classrooms, fields, playgrounds, tennis and basketball courts, and gymnasiums continue to remain closed during this time. We hoped to avoid these actions but feel they are necessary to protect the health of our students, families, staff and the public by preserving physical distancing in our community and slowing the spread of coronavirus. Please see a letter to the community from Supt. Dr. Andrew Pulver. bit.ly/EndYearClosure

post_text:
Hopkinson Elementary teacher Jill Shafer:
"When I knew we were closing, I wanted to find a way to reach my kids. I took 5-6 addresses each night and went out around 8pm. I wanted them to come out in the morning, see it, and smile. I know there is so much uncertainty right now, but I wanted my kids to know that I'm still cheering them on! I chalked 28 of my 30 students. The two that I couldn't reach live in apartments, so I sent them a card."😍 #losalbettertogether

As you know, we are closely monitoring the coronavirus situation and have been actively planning for the possible closure of schools for a minimum of two weeks as a means of slowing the spread of the disease and helping to keep our students and families safe.

Our District Board of Education is holding an emergency meeting today at 2:30 PM to consider in closed session closing our campuses to students as early as Monday. Following the Board meeting, we will update you about our plans and how we will provide instruction and other essential services during any period of closure.

post_text: An unclaimed backpack was found this morning in an office at Los Alamitos High School. On recommendation of Los Alamitos Police, all students were safely moved to the designated evacuation area. The Orange County Sheriff bomb squad responded and determined that the contents of the backpack were harmless. A Los Alamitos police search of the campus found no threats. About 10 AM, Los Alamitos PD declared an all clear and students returned to class￼ to resume the school day.

post_text: A custom-built, 3200-lb laser metal-cutting machine is finally at home in the Los Alamitos High engineering lab as part of the school's commitment to Career and Technical Education. Construction experts made sure the floor would hold the weight and machine-moving specialists were called in to transport it across campus. In the end, it was a close squeak (watch the video!) but a successful installation. Students will use the high-precision equipment to manufacture robot and automotive parts, metal enclosures, jewelry and other objects.

post_text: It's official! After a five-month process of considering 11 draft maps and gathering input from our community at 35 public meetings, our Board of Education has adopted the GREEN 4 map as we shift from at-large school board elections to trustee-area voting. Once approved by the county and state, the map will be used for elections starting in November of this year. Full details and background: https://www.losal.org/voting

post_text: Thea Rodrigue, a volunteer and school parent, is the Los Alamitos Elementary 2019-20 Hero of the Heart. “I can’t thank her enough for all of the time, energy, and dedication to helping all of our students receive an all-around incredible educational experience,” said Principal Gary Willems. post_text:
Mai Tran, a volunteer and school parent, is the McAuliffe Middle School 2019-20 Hero of the Heart. Tran, who has a daughter at McAuliffe and two other children at Weaver Elementary, has been choir booster vice president and costume coordinator, event chair for the school’s A Cappella Café, PTA organizer for both Teacher Appreciation week and the Honorary Service Award event, Copy Angel and balloon designer for school events.
She is a “selfless volunteer who never wants to be dragged into the spotlight but whose light burns too bright to only keep to ourselves,” said Asst. Principal Cara Vienna.
Congratulations, Mai Tran!

She is a “selfless volunteer who never wants to be dragged into the spotlight but whose light burns too bright to only keep to ourselves,” said Asst. Principal Cara Vienna.
Congratulations, Mai Tran!

post_text:
We have posted FIVE draft maps of new trustee areas for electing school board members on our website at http://bit.ly/losalmaps for community members to review, along with an interactive tool for comparing the maps. A series of community outreach meetings will be held next week to solicit public comment on the draft maps before the Board votes on a final version in January.

•Mon., Nov. 4, 6:30 PM, Rush Park, Rossmoor.
•Tues., Nov. 5, 2:00 PM, Clubhouse 3 Rm. 2, Leisure World.
•Tues., Nov. 5, 6:30 PM, McGaugh Elementary auditorium in Seal Beach.
•Wed., Nov. 6, 6:30 PM, District Office Board Room in Los Alamitos.

The Board also will hold formal public hearings on the draft maps Nov. 12 and Dec. 10 as part of its regular meetings beginning at 6:30 PM in the District Office Board Room.

Comment also can be submitted via email: trusteeareaelection@losal.org

shared_text:
Los Al Unified is at Los Alamitos Unified School District.
May 3, 2019 at 11:35 AM · Cypress, CA ·

Erin Lawrence, a longtime nurse for our schools, has been named the Orange County Coordinating School Nurse of the Year. The Orange County School Nurses Organization honored Lawrence, who has been with the district for 20 years, for her work in advocating for children, helping families deal with serious health issues or serving as a role model for colleagues and students. Congratulations!
